  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several key ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Agreements\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- These establish global standards and expectations for anti-money laundering (AML) efforts\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries cooperate in investigating and prosecuting money laundering\n- Sharing evidence and intelligence across jurisdictions\n- Extradition agreements for financial crimes\n\n3. Compliance Requirements\n- Banks and financial institutions must follow international AML regulations\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Cross-border transaction monitoring\n\n4. Sanctions and Enforcement\n- International bodies can impose sanctions on countries with weak AML frameworks\n- Coordinated enforcement actions against transnational financial crimes\n- Economic pressure to improve regulatory standards\n\n5. Harmonization of Legal Frameworks\n- Countries increasingly align their national laws with international standards\n- Developing consistent definitions of money laundering\n- Creating similar investigative and prosecutorial mechanisms\n\nThese intersections aim to create a comprehensive global approach to preventing financial crimes.",
